  <li id="comment-2119" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/04225535216850178185" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Emily</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2005/05/rhubarb-better-late-than-never-and-right-on-time/#comment-2119"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2008-04-10T03:21:00-04:00">Thursday, April 10, 2008 at 3:21 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I&#8217;m massively behind the times with this one, so I apologize in advance!</>I saw the first rhubarb of the season last week, and instantly grabbed two handfuls and raced home to find a good recipe for them.  I found yours and immediately set to work to get those gorgeous stalks in the oven.  Mmmm&#8230;.pure bliss.  </>I grew up on straight rhubarb pie and rhubarb crisp (no fancy schmany strawberry mixture for us!) and this was absolutely what I was looking for.  I added a touch of vanilla extract and served it with yogurt (no fresh ricotta at the market) and it was quite lovely.</>Thank you, Molly!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-2119' data-commentid="2119" data-postid="1745" data-belowelement="comment-2119" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Emily" aria-label='Reply to Emily'>Reply</a>    </div>
